Brexit, and what next?
NEW YORK – It will take a long time for the United Kingdom, Europe, and the world as a whole to digest the implications of the Brexit referendum led by the United Kingdom.
The deepest consequences will, of course, depend on the European Union's response to the United Kingdom's withdrawal.
Most people initially believed that the EU would not "cut off the branch it was sitting on": after all, a friendly divorce seems to be in everyone's interest.
But the divorce – as is often the case – could become complicated.
The benefits of economic and commercial integration between the United Kingdom and the EU are reciprocal, and if the EU took seriously its conviction that greater economic integration is desirable, its leaders would seek to ensure that the ties remain as close as possible given the circumstances.
Or, Jean-Claude Juncker, the architect of massive tax avoidance schemes benefiting companies in Luxembourg and now president of the European Commission, seems to be adopting a hard line: "Out means out," he declared.
This instinctive reaction may be understandable, given that Juncker could be seen as the one who presided over the first stage of the EU's dissolution.
He argues that, in order to dissuade other countries from leaving, the EU must accept no compromise, offering the United Kingdom barely more than what is guaranteed by the World Trade Organization agreements.
In other words, the European Union should not be kept united by the benefits it offers its members, which far exceed its costs.
Economic prosperity, the sense of solidarity, and pride in being European are not enough, according to Juncker.
No, the European Union must be held together by threats, intimidation, and fear.
This position ignores a lesson that clearly emerged, both in the Brexit vote and in the Republican primary elections in the United States: a large part of the population has suffered greatly in recent times.
The neoliberal agenda of the past four decades may have been good for the top 1% of the wealthiest, but not for the rest of the population.
I had long predicted that this stagnation would eventually have political consequences.
This day has now arrived.
On both sides of the Atlantic, citizens consider trade agreements to be the source of their misfortunes.
Although it is an excessive simplification, it is understandable.
The trade agreements of today are negotiated in secret, ensuring good representation of corporate interests but complete exclusion of ordinary citizens or workers.
Without surprise, the results were one-sided: the workers' negotiation position has further weakened, exacerbating the effects of legislation that reduces the influence of unions and the rights of employees.
Although trade agreements have played a role in creating these inequalities, many other factors have contributed to shifting the political balance in favor of capital.
Intellectual property rules, for example, have increased the power of pharmaceutical companies to raise prices.
However, any increase in the market power of companies inevitably leads to a decline in real wages— an increase in inequality that has become a characteristic of most advanced countries today.
In many sectors, industrial concentration is increasing—and the same goes for market power.
The effects of stagnation and the decline in real wages have added to those of austerity, which has threatened cuts in public services that so many low- and middle-income workers depend on.
The economic uncertainty that results for workers, when combined with migration, has created a toxic mix.
Many refugees are victims of wars and oppression to which the West has contributed.
Providing aid is a moral responsibility for all, but especially for the former colonial powers.
And yet, although many would probably deny it, an increase in the supply of unskilled labor leads—so long as we are in the presence of normal downward-sloping demand curves—to a decrease in equilibrium wages.
And when wages cannot fall, unemployment rises.
This is particularly concerning in countries where poor economic management has already led to a high level of overall unemployment.
Europe, particularly the eurozone, has been very poorly managed over the last few decades, to the extent that its average unemployment rate is now in double digits.
Unrestricted migration in Europe means that the countries which have more successfully reduced unemployment will inevitably end up hosting more than their fair share of refugees.
Workers in these countries bear the cost of depressed wages and higher unemployment, while employers benefit from a cheaper labor force.
The burden of refugees, as expected, is borne by those who are least able to bear it.
Of course, there is a lot of talk about the net benefits of immigration.
For a country offering a low level of guaranteed benefits—social protection, education, healthcare, etc.—to all its citizens, this may be the case.
But for countries that provide a decent social safety net, the opposite is true.
The result of all this downward pressure on wages and cuts to public services has been the hollowing out of the middle class, with similar consequences on both sides of the Atlantic.
Middle-class and working-class households have not benefited from economic growth.
They understand that banks caused the 2008 crisis; but they then saw billions allocated to save the banks, and insignificant amounts to save their homes and jobs.
While the median real (inflation-adjusted) income for a full-time male worker in the United States is lower than it was four decades ago, the anger of the electorate should come as no surprise.
Moreover, politicians who promised change have not met expectations.
Ordinary citizens knew the system was unfair, but they began to see it as even more rigged than they had imagined, thereby losing the little remaining trust they still had in the ability or willingness of traditional politicians to fix it.
This too is understandable: the new politicians shared the perspectives of those who had promised that globalization would be beneficial for everyone.
However, a vote of anger does not solve the problems, and may instead lead to a political and economic situation that is even worse.
The same applies if one responds with anger to a vote.
Forgetting the past is a fundamental principle in economics.
On both sides of the Channel, politics must now seek to understand how, in a democracy, the political establishment could have done so little to address the concerns of so many citizens.
Each government of the EU must now consider the improvement of the well-being of ordinary citizens as its main objective.
More neoliberal ideology will not help.
And we should stop conflating objectives and means: for example, free trade, if well managed, could bring about greater shared prosperity; but if poorly managed, it will certainly reduce the standard of living of many—perhaps the majority—of citizens.
There are alternatives to the current neoliberal policies that could create shared prosperity, just as there are alternatives—such as the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership agreement with the EU proposed by President Barack Obama—that would cause much more harm.
The challenge today is to learn from the past, in order to adopt the first and avoid the second.
